      Nvidia 13F
   =20
 =20

Last Wednesday, Nvidia Corp. filed a  Form 13F with the US Securities and E=
xchange Commission disclosing what stocks it owns. The list is short =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0five names =E2=80=94=C2=A0and includes=C2=A0a $147 million stake i=
n Arm Holdings Plc,=C2=A0$3.7 million worth of a small artificial intellige=
nce company called=C2=A0SoundHound AI Inc. and $379,856 worth of a small me=
dical device company called=C2=A0Nano-X Imaging Inc. The day after that fil=
ing, the stocks of SoundHound and Nano-X soared, because   Nvidia is =E2=80=
=9Cthe most important stock on planet earth,=E2=80=9D and if Nvidia wanted =
SoundHound and Nano-X stock then so did a lot of other people.=C2=A0
We   talked about this last week. The oddity of it is that all of this was =
public information already, more or less. Nvidia invested in SoundHound in =
2017.=C2=A0SoundHound put out a  press release touting the investment, and =
Bloomberg News   covered=C2=A0it. When SoundHound went public in 2022, it  =
again boasted that it had Nvidia as an investor. Nano-X was a   more compli=
cated trail: Nvidia also invested in a company called Zebra Medical Vision =
in 2017 (here=E2=80=99s  the press release, naming Nvidia as an investor), =
and Nano-X acquired Zebra in 2021 in an all-stock deal (here=E2=80=99s the =
 press release). So you could have read those press releases and thought =
=E2=80=9Cwell, Nvidia bought shares in Zebra, those shares got swapped for =
shares in Nano-X, so Nvidia owns some Nano-X now,=E2=80=9D and you=E2=80=99=
d have been right. You=C2=A0could=C2=A0have been wrong =E2=80=94=C2=A0Nvidi=
a could have dumped those shares after the acquisition =E2=80=94=C2=A0but y=
ou would have been right.
Nvidia's 13F filing was also more or less predictable. Nvidia had never fil=
ed a 13F =E2=80=94=C2=A0never disclosed its stock holdings in an easy-to-fi=
nd place =E2=80=94=C2=A0before, but=C2=A0SEC rules require companies that o=
wn more than $100 million worth of publicly traded stock to file Form 13F, =
beginning the year after they cross that $100 million threshold. The Form 1=
3F has to disclose the company=E2=80=99s holdings of public stock, and the =
deadline is 45 days after the end of the previous quarter, meaning Feb. 14,=
 which is exactly when Nvidia  filed its form. Arm  went public last Septem=
ber, and it prominently disclosed that Nvidia would be one of the =E2=80=9C=
cornerstone investors=E2=80=9D in its $4.9 billion initial public offering.=
 Based on that disclosure, you could have guessed that Nvidia=E2=80=99s Arm=
 stake would=C2=A0be above $100 million.
  [2]
=C2=A0Again, that guess=C2=A0could=C2=A0have been wrong =E2=80=94=C2=A0I ha=
ve not seen any official disclosure of the size of Nvidia=E2=80=99s Arm inv=
estment before=C2=A0the 13F =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it was a reasonable guess an=
d turned out to be right.
Also it=E2=80=99s worth pointing out that =E2=80=9C13F day=E2=80=9D is a th=
ing: Most 13F filers file right at the quarterly deadline, many 13F filers =
are prominent investors (hedge fund managers, Warren Buffett, Cathie Wood),=
 and people pay=C2=A0attention=C2=A0to their filings. Journalists write up =
the stocks that they have bought and sold, those stories get a lot of reade=
rs, and other investors sometimes copy their moves. A 13F disclosing that a=
 celebrity investor bought a small stock=C2=A0in December can cause that st=
ock to rally in February.
So if you were familiar with Arm=E2=80=99s IPO prospectus, and the SEC=E2=
=80=99s ownership disclosure rules, and seven years=E2=80=99 worth of press=
 releases from small-cap tech companies like SoundHound and Nano-X and Zebr=
a Medical Vision, and the financial media=E2=80=99s reporting=C2=A0of 13F f=
ilings, and the popular=C2=A0interest=C2=A0that makes Nvidia=E2=80=99s move=
s worth following,=C2=A0you could have formed the following thesis last mon=
th:
=09Nvidia probably owns stakes in SoundHound and Nano-X.=09It will probably=
 have to file a Form 13F disclosing those stakes.=09It will probably do tha=
t on Feb. 14.=09When that happens, there will probably be a lot of news sto=
ries to the effect of =E2=80=9CNvidia owns SoundHound and Nano-X.=E2=80=9D=
=09People will pay attention to those stories and copy Nvidia=E2=80=99s mov=
es.=09Nano-X and SoundHound, which are quite small companies, will benefit =
a lot from that attention, and their stocks will go up a lot.=09Therefore, =
just before the 13F deadline (say, Monday, Feb. 12), I should buy out-of-th=
e money call options on Nano-X and SoundHound that expire just after the de=
adline (say, Friday, Feb. 16). Those options will be cheap, and if this the=
sis is right, they=C2=A0will benefit maximally from the Nvidia-induced pop.

How likely is it that anyone had that thought process? It seems reasonable =
as I lay it out in hindsight, but there are a lot of steps. I suppose that =
if you are an obsessive tracker of Nvidia =E2=80=94=C2=A0and I guess there =
are a lot of those? =E2=80=94=C2=A0you might follow all of its investments,=
 know about SoundHound and Zebra/Nano-X, know about Arm, know (from your ge=
neral knowledge of US financial markets) about the 13F rules, and put all t=
he pieces together to buy some SoundHound and Nano-X options. Or if you are=
 a devoted longtime investor in=C2=A0SoundHound=C2=A0or=C2=A0Nano-X, you mi=
ght look for catalysts,=C2=A0know that Nvidia is a prominent shareholder in=
 your favorite little company, pay some attention to Nvidia=E2=80=99s other=
 doings, and realize that those doings might provide your catalyst.=C2=A0
Or I suppose if you are some omniscient ingester of market information =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0if you somehow have=C2=A0every press release from every company=
 lodged in your memory, and every IPO prospectus, and every SEC rule, and y=
ou have a robust data set showing the effects various sorts of news have on=
 various stock prices, and you have the processing power to test millions o=
f possible connections to see if you can find anything meaningful =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0then you might have found this signal. Maybe there is some quant fund=
 somewhere whose model saw the connections and told it to buy Nano-X calls =
on Feb. 12.
I don=E2=80=99t know? If you, or your model,=C2=A0did come up with this the=
sis based on public information, email me; I=E2=80=99ll be impressed. Anywa=
y, someone did buy those call options.=C2=A0The Financial Times reports:

Traders placed an unusually large number of bets on two obscure companies a=
t the start of last week, days before a disclosure by chipmaker Nvidia trig=
gered a furious rally in their shares. ...
Two days before Nvidia=E2=80=99s filing, traders bought thousands of short-=
term options contracts that would pay out if there was a sharp jump in Nano=
-X=E2=80=99s stock. ...
The bulk of the trades were for a contract that expired on Friday and gave =
the right to buy Nano-X stock for $7.50 per share =E2=80=94 42 per cent les=
s than Friday=E2=80=99s eventual closing price or $12.95.
The trader or traders paid between 4 and 30 cents a contract on February 12=
. On Friday the same contracts changed hands for as much as $6.40, a trough=
 to peak increase of almost 16,000 per cent.
Investors traded more than six times the average volume of SoundHound call =
options on February 9, and more than three times the average volume on Febr=
uary 12. Unlike with Nano-X, however, the volume of put options =E2=80=94 w=
hich offer protection against a share price decline =E2=80=94 was also high=
er than normal.
Henry Hu, a professor of finance at the University of Texas, said some trad=
ers appeared to have been betting that other investors would =E2=80=9Coverr=
eact=E2=80=9D to immaterial news because of =E2=80=9Cthe magic dust of AI=
=E2=80=9D.

Sure right that was the=C2=A0bet, and it was correct. But how did they know=
 to bet on Nano-X? Obsessive tracking of Nano-X? Of Nvidia? Omniscient trac=
king of everything? Or =E2=80=A6 ? You know?=C2=A0I   wrote last week:
I hope someone in Nvidia=E2=80=99s legal department bought a ton of short-d=
ated SoundHound call options yesterday! What a fun insider trading case=C2=
=A0that=C2=A0would be. If you knew that Nvidia was about to=C2=A0re-disclos=
e its stake in SoundHound, was that material nonpublic information? It was =
kind of public already. And yet it moved the stock.
Right? The news about Nvidia=E2=80=99s investments in Nano-X and SoundHound=
 was=C2=A0both=C2=A0public=C2=A0and=C2=A0immaterial, and yet it quite=C2=A0=
predictably=C2=A0moved the stocks.=C2=A0And is it more likely that someone =
bought these options because they saw the draft 13F a week before it was fi=
led, or because they remembered the Zebra Medical fundraising deal in 2017 =
and the Nano-X/Zebra acquisition in 2021 and realized that the Arm IPO woul=
d trigger an Nvidia 13F?

