Two things that were true about the recent crypto boom are:
=09People were very enthusiastic about a lot of very transparently dumb ide=
as, so crypto entrepreneurs could raise a lot of money from people for very=
 stupid purposes without lying to anyone at all, and=09Also a lot of crypto=
 entrepreneurs raised a lot of money from people by lying to them.

I mean! You could, and people did, raise millions of dollars for utterly no=
nsensical token projects by saying things like =E2=80=9Cthis project will r=
eplace all banks and generate trillions of dollars of revenue by next month=
.=E2=80=9D And you could, and people did, raise millions of dollars for utt=
erly nonsensical token projects by saying things like =E2=80=9Cthis project=
 is utterly nonsensical, let=E2=80=99s see how much=C2=A0money it can raise=
, lol.=E2=80=9D Some early Ethereum projects had   names like =E2=80=9CEthe=
reum Pyramid Contract.=E2=80=9D Dogecoin=C2=A0still=C2=A0has a market capit=
alization of  almost $12 billion.=C2=A0
Broadly speaking =E2=80=94=C2=A0and oh boy is this not legal advice =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0raising money for dumb crypto projects=C2=A0by lying=C2=A0is fraud=
 and will get you in trouble, while raising money for dumb crypto projects =
by just transparently giving people the dumb things they want is, uh, proba=
bly not technically fraud, but when they wake up from their mania they will=
 be mad at you. And there are lots of gray areas.
So for a while the biggest algorithmic stablecoin in crypto was TerraUSD, t=
he stablecoin of the Terra blockchain, which attracted billions of dollars =
of investment. Terra was pretty clear about the mechanism by which TerraUSD=
 held its value, and that mechanism was   pretty clearly nonsensical, and e=
ventually all of that value was evaporated in an extremely predictable and =
predicted way. At some level, people got exactly the dumb gamble they were =
told about, with full disclosure. But=C2=A0also=C2=A0Do Kwon, the founder o=
f Terra,  is currently in jail,=C2=A0has been  accused of lots of fraud, an=
d does=C2=A0seem to have lied about things (including how widely used Terra=
 was) that would be material to a reasonable investor.
But I think the most interesting case is that of Three Arrows Capital. Thre=
e Arrows =E2=80=94=C2=A0or 3AC, as it was usually called =E2=80=94=C2=A0was=
 a crypto trading firm founded by Kyle Davies and Su Zhu. It   pursued a st=
rategy of (1)   borrowing enormous amounts of money from crypto lending pla=
tforms, with little or no collateral or due diligence, because those lender=
s were desperate to lend their money to someone and Davies and Zhu seemed n=
ice, (2) investing that money in risky trades that, for a while, made Davie=
s and Zhu a lot of money, and then (3) fairly predictably blowing up and le=
aving several of the lenders (though not Davies or Zhu!) bankrupt.
Since the collapse, Davies and Zhu have made lots of public statements to t=
he effect of =E2=80=9Cyeah those lenders were dumb and desperate to give us=
 money so we took it.=E2=80=9D But they tend to make those statements from =
not-entirely-disclosed locations. Did they commit any crimes? No? No-ish? I=
 don=E2=80=99t know? Certainly their=C2=A0view is that they are a pure exam=
ple of=C2=A0transparently giving=C2=A0people the dumb thing they wanted, bu=
t probably their lenders disagree. (Eventually Zhu was arrested a little bi=
t, but he=E2=80=99s out now, and his arrest was for not cooperating with 3A=
C=E2=80=99s liquidators, not for any allegations of fraud.)
Today at New York Magazine, Jen Wieczner has a  very fun update on Zhu and =
Davies, mentioning their not-entirely-disclosed locations:
In February, Davies told me he was in Portugal. In the year and a half prio=
r, he had bounced around between Bali, Spain, and other parts of Europe. Bu=
t when I pressed him on specific regions =E2=80=94 Lisbon? Surf villages? W=
ine country? =E2=80=94 he declined to respond.=C2=A0
And Zhu=E2=80=99s apparently chill time in jail:
Zhu framed his incarceration as an almost Nelson Mandela=E2=80=93like exper=
ience of transformation and enlightenment, speaking of how it sharpened his=
