<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I guess there are three ways to <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34425851.257383/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
d3NqLmNvbS9maW5hbmNlL3N0b2Nrcy9yZWRkaXQtc3RvY2staXBvLWJ1eWVycy11c2Vycy01ODc=
0NDQ0Nj9tb2Q9aHBfbGVhZF9wb3M1/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB704da46f" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 look at this</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Reddit plans to place a big chunk of its IPO s=
hares in the hands of its users, an unusual move that could build loyalty b=
ut also comes with risk.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The company plans to reserve an as-yet-undeter=
mined number of shares for 75,000 of its most prolific so-called redditors =
when it goes public next month, according to people familiar with the matte=
r. The users will have the opportunity to buy Reddit shares at its initial =
public offering price before the stock starts trading, a privilege normally=
 reserved only for big investors.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ideally for the company and its underwriters, =
Reddit shares will rise in their stock-market debut, bestowing big gains on=
 those who buy in at the IPO price. If the stock falls, however, it could a=
nger those members of Reddit=E2=80=99s community =E2=80=94 a group that, br=
oadly speaking, hasn=E2=80=99t shied away from boycotts in the past.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Banks generally favor selling the bulk of an I=
PO to big money managers that tend to hold stocks for a relatively long tim=
e. Individual investors are viewed as more fickle and prone to selling at t=
he first sign of weakness.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One is the sort of philosophical view. Reddit =
Inc., more so even than most social media companies,=C2=A0is a publisher th=
at doesn=E2=80=99t pay its writers and editors. It runs a website that publ=
ishes huge amounts of content on various message boards; the boards are mos=
tly moderated by volunteers and the content is written by users. From this,=
 Reddit generates hundreds of millions of dollars of <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34425851.257383/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21i=
ZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDItMDUvcmVkZGl0LXMtcmV2ZW51ZS1yaXNlcy0=
yMC1haGVhZC1vZi1pcG8tYnV0LWlzbi10LXByb2ZpdGFibGUteWV0P2NtcGlkPUJCRDAyMjEyNF=
9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90Z=
XJtPTI0MDIyMSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc502=
1a01" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-=
color: #ccc;">  revenue</a> from ads and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/34425851.257383/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cucmVkZGl0LmNvbS9yL3Jl=
ZGRpdC9jb21tZW50cy8xNDVicmFtL2FkZHJlc3NpbmdfdGhlX2NvbW11bml0eV9hYm91dF9jaGF=
uZ2VzX3RvX291cl9hcGkv/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBefa11fec" itemprop=3D"StoryL=
ink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> data</a>.=
 For the most part, the users do not really share in that revenue.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This model=C2=A0<em>works fine =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
</em>It is in fact the case that the users happily post and moderate on Red=
dit without getting paid! There is no need to pay them! =E2=80=94=C2=A0but =
it is=C2=A0<em>awkward</em>, particularly when=C2=A0an initial public offer=
ing is set to value the company at <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbu=
siness.com/click/34425851.257383/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2=
FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDEtMjgvcmVkZGl0LWFkdmlzZWQtdG8tdGFyZ2V0LWF0LWxlYXN0LTUtY=
mlsbGlvbi12YWx1YXRpb24taW4taXBvP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAyMjEyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9t=
ZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDIyMSZ1dG1fY2F=
tcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd5726f7b" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">more tha=
n=C2=A0$5 billion</a>. =E2=80=9CWe created $5 billion of value and get none=
 of it,=E2=80=9D some redditors will probably complain.=C2=A0Letting them b=
uy stock at the IPO price doesn=E2=80=99t <em>really=C2=A0</em>address that=
 complaint =E2=80=94=C2=A0they still have to pay for it! =E2=80=94=C2=A0but=
 it sort of symbolically responds to it. =E2=80=9CWe let our users share in=
 our success, by paying full price for the stock,=E2=80=9D Reddit can say; =
it=E2=80=99s fine, whatever.<span><a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#foot=
note-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !=
important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;=
">
<span>[1]</span>
</a></span></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The second is the conventional capital markets=
 view. Here, the rough idea is that banks sell the stock in an IPO mostly t=
o big institutional investors, most of whom they expect to buy and hold the=
 stock. Then the next day, the stock opens for trading, and lots of people =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0institutions that didn=E2=80=99t get allocations, but also r=
etail investors =E2=80=94=C2=A0want to buy it. But there=E2=80=99s not a lo=
t for sale, because most of the IPO was placed with long-term holders. So t=
here=E2=80=99s a lot=C2=A0of demand and not much supply, so the stock goes =
up, creating an =E2=80=9CIPO pop.=E2=80=9D This means that it is generally =
good to get an allocation in the IPO: You buy stock in the IPO, and the nex=
t day it reasonably predictably goes up and you make money. And retail inve=
stors mostly don=E2=80=99t get to buy a lot of stock in IPOs, so they miss =
out on this pop.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Letting individual redditors buy stock in the =
IPO sort of addresses this problem: The redditors get to buy stock at the i=
nstitutional price, and then it goes up and they make money. On the other h=
and, if you let the retail investors buy in the IPO, that kind of ruins the=
 mechanism that leads to the IPO pop? The devoted retail investors who want=
 to buy the stock=C2=A0<em>do so in the IPO</em>, rather than having to wai=
t until the next day, so there=E2=80=99s not as much demand when the stock =
opens for trading. And a lot of those retail investors might be looking to =
make a quick buck by flipping the stock, so there is more supply. So there=
=E2=80=99s less reason to expect a pop. =E2=80=9CIf everyone buys at the IP=
O price then there=E2=80=99ll be no one waiting to buy it the next day,=E2=
=80=9D <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34425851.25=
7383/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDctMj=
gvcm9iaW5ob29kLXVzZXJzLWdldC10by1vd24tcm9iaW5ob29kP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAyMjEyNF9NT=
05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJt=
PTI0MDIyMSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa21e0c9=
1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">  I wrote</a>, when Robinhood Markerts Inc. tried this sort of=
 thing,=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cand everyone who bought it to make a quick profit wil=
l be selling it at a loss.=E2=80=9D (That <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/34425851.257383/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9=
vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDgtMDQvdGhlLXNlYy1oYXMtaXRzLWV5ZS1vbi1jcnlwdG=
8_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDIyMTI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlP=
W5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwMjIxJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cBda5c31e9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;">    did happen to Robinhood</a>, though=
 then it rallied hard the week after its IPO, so who knows.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The third is the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/34425851.257383/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmN=
vbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDgtMjIvbWVtZS1zdG9jay12YWNhdGlvbi1pcy1vdm=
VyP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAyMjEyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZ=
T1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDIyMSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f0=
7ceef4b8524a319a23cBe8abfbbe" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  meme-stock</a> corporate finance vi=
ew.=C2=A0Most companies are mostly owned by big institutional investors,=C2=
=A0there are fairly traditional ways to keep those investors happy (steadil=
y increasing earnings, clear communications, stock buybacks, etc.),=C2=A0ke=
eping those investors happy keeps the stock price up, and a high stock pric=
e is good for the executives (who get paid largely in stock) and for the co=
mpany (if it ever needs to raise money by selling more=C2=A0stock). But in =
the 2020s,=C2=A0<em>some=C2=A0</em>companies are owned in large part by ret=
ail investors, and some of those investors are more interested in being par=
t of an online community of investors, and trading jokes and memes, than th=
ey are in financial analysis. And=C2=A0you can make <em>those</em> investor=
